The article discusses the relationship between corporate tax rate reductions and the incomes of American workers. It argues that taxes on production, such as corporate income taxes, reduce economic activity in an economy. When factories are not built and equipment is not purchased due to high taxes, workers experience lower wages and fewer job opportunities. The article also highlights that in a globalized world, the size of corporate income tax rates in different countries determines where new factories are built. The article suggests that reducing corporate tax rates is important to attract investment and create more jobs. It addresses criticisms of corporate tax cuts, arguing that they can benefit both workers and firms by stimulating economic activity. The article concludes by emphasizing that reducing corporate taxes does not simply transfer money from the government to households, but rather encourages investment and economic growth.